The National Women=E2=80=99s Soccer League is about to start its 13th seaso=
n with a
ton of momentum. Last season, the league set viewership and attendance reco=
rds (over 17 million total broadcast viewers); it started a new media deal =
with some of the biggest companies in the business (ESPN, CBS, Amazon Prime=
 Video, Scripps); and it developed crossover stars (Trinity Rodman, Sophia =
Smith, Mallory Swanson, etcetera). The league=E2=80=99s commissioner, Jessi=
ca Berman, joined the Varsity
podcast yesterday to discuss how she can continue that momentum going into =
this season.

Berman=E2=80=99s game plan was clear. The actual soccer must be top-quality=
, and the league has to do everything it can to help its players and teams =
become even more culturally relevant. In our conversation, Berman highlight=
ed the Amazon Prime Series For the Win, which is the league=E2=80=99s first=
 docuseries. She also called on players to be more willing to tell their st=
ories
publicly to draw in casual fans. As always, this conversation has been ligh=
tly edited.

The Power of Storylines
-----------------------

John Ourand: You have peace
with the union. You set an attendance record last year. Your championship g=
ame set a viewership record. As the commissioner of the NWSL, where will yo=
ur focus be?

=C2=A0

Jessica Berman: One area where we are laser focused is on transcending cult=
ural relevance to ensure that more people know the amazing stories of our a=
thletes and the teams. Creating cultural relevance and
discoverability through storytelling is our primary focus on the fan side. =
We spent a lot of time last season learning about our audience, and figurin=
g out who the addressable audience is. What you=E2=80=99re now going to see=
 is partnerships that are specifically, and intentionally, going after the =
audience segment that we know and believe, based on our data and research, =
would be most interested in the NWSL.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

One of the ways we=E2=80=99re doing that is through original content. We la=
unched our first ever docuseries on Amazon Prime on March 6. It=E2=80=99s c=
alled For the Win, and it followed our eight playoff teams from the quarter=
finals to the semifinals to the final.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I=E2=80=99ve seen that in practice. As you know, I live in the D.C. market,=
 where the Washington Spirit=E2=80=99s Trinity Rodman is probably better kn=
own
than any D.C. United player or Washington Mystics player.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

She=E2=80=99s a perfect example, because she tells her story in a really au=
thentic way in the docuseries. She=E2=80=99s also putting herself out there=
 more, with our encouragement. She was on Alex Cooper=E2=80=99s Call Her Da=
ddy podcast, where millions of people had the chance to hear her story. Tri=
nity is a huge
unlock to the casual fan.

=C2=A0

What are other leagues doing well?

=C2=A0

The NHL 4 Nations Face-Off was something I really paid attention to. It was=
 interesting to see the way people were so interested in getting behind the=
ir nationalities and the countries that are represented in the league. Ther=
e=E2=80=99s a lot of
analogies to what we have in our league, such as the way the NHL has repres=
entation globally=E2=80=94it doesn=E2=80=99t only have American athletes. P=
art of what made that interesting was that there was real competition from =
other countries.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

What could the NWSL learn from that?=C2=A0

=C2=A0

At its base level, it
reinforces what we already know, which is that people really care about the=
 national tournaments. And, of course, soccer is like the ultimate proof ca=
se with the World Cup and the Olympics. It=E2=80=99s the question of how yo=
u create, market, and scale an event like the 4 Nations Face-Off. More impo=
rtantly for the NHL, the challenge becomes taking that excitement and bring=
ing it back into the regular season. For example, our league couldn=E2=80=
=99t have had a more successful Olympics in 2024. We worked really
hard to bring that tailwind into our league.

=C2=A0

Did you feel that tailwind? Because hockey does great in the Olympics, but =
the NHL generally doesn=E2=80=99t see an uptick in TV viewership afterward.=
 Olympic basketball was great, but the NBA saw their early-season viewershi=
p actually drop significantly.

=C2=A0

You have
to define the metrics you=E2=80=99re looking for. There may or may not be a=
 tailwind that=E2=80=99s directly tied to the next week, or the next month.=
 But it is fair to say that we experienced positive indicators around the s=
uccess of the Olympics, and players like the Triple Espresso trio of Sophia=
 Smith, Mallory Swanson, and Trinity Rodman.

=C2=A0

It=E2=80=99s easy to identify the low-hanging fruit that you=E2=80=99re loo=
king for, like TV ratings or
attendance. And of course those are important. To the extent that happens, =
it=E2=80=99s great. But it=E2=80=99s also important to look at some of the =
other things that you might see.

The TV Conundrum
----------------

The NWSL is one year into the media rights deal with ESPN, CBS, Amazon
Prime Video, and Scripps. Give us a report card.

=C2=A0

The most important priority in that media deal was to increase discoverabil=
ity, to make sure that our games were in the places and spaces where people=
 consume live content, and we accomplished that in spades. From 2023 to 202=
4, total viewership on our broadcasts through the regular season and playof=
fs went from about 4 million to over 17 million.
The second thing we wanted to accomplish is to reset the value of our right=
s. We definitely did that.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The challenge we have as we go into year two of the deal is to begin to bui=
ld audience and consumer habits around viewership. Knowing that we have our=
 games across four platforms=E2=80=94and to make sure that we=E2=80=99re en=
gaging in more top-of-funnel marketing awareness, more broad marketing init=
iatives and
strategies to put our athletes and our storylines about rivalries and thing=
s that might pique people=E2=80=99s interest=E2=80=94we need to give them t=
he reason why they should watch. Because we know now that if they turn on t=
heir TV, they might actually just stumble on our game.

=C2=A0

A consistent criticism for many sports is that it=E2=80=99s become too diff=
icult to find games. You have deals with four media companies. Did you
see any red flags there?

=C2=A0

People complained about the idea of it before it was in place. When we anno=
unced, there was definitely concern about it. But once our season started, =
we saw almost no pushback. The good news here is that we=E2=80=99re not dif=
ferent. We=E2=80=99re not asking our fans, or future fans, to do something =
that no one else is asking them to do. The not-so-good news is that it suck=
s for the sports
fan. If I want to watch a game, I Google to figure out where I can find it,=
 or I ask my 14-year-old, who knows everything. There=E2=80=99s a lot of sm=
art people trying to figure out how to solve this. I know one of our partne=
rs, ESPN, is working hard on a =E2=80=9CWatch Now=E2=80=9D feature, where e=
ven if it=E2=80=99s not on their own platform, you can directly link to the=
 game.

=C2=A0

You have three more years left on your media deal.
When do you start to negotiate a new one?

=C2=A0

Maybe this comes from my collective bargaining background, which is a very =
different kind of contract, and a very different kind of negotiation: The d=
iscussions on your next deal begin the second you sign your deal. Everythin=
g that we=E2=80=99re doing is with an eye toward our next deal, and that al=
l started in November of 2023.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

What are you looking at to help you come up with a strategy?

=C2=A0

We try to think about it through the lens of the things we can control. The=
 industry is going to change so much in the next six months, 12 months, 18 =
months. We obviously are going to keep tabs on that, and stay close to peop=
le whom I respect and trust, and who
are strategic and informed.

It=E2=80=99s not just viewership numbers. It=E2=80=99s the demographics of =
your audience, and how that relates to brands. It=E2=80=99s about getting r=
eally sophisticated about data and research and analytics, both on our own =
and with our partners.=C2=A0

